# Fed Declining To Ease Rates, Citing Inflation

Prolonging a Period of High Interest

By JEANNA SMILAK

WASHINGTON — Federal Reserve officials told investors rates unwinding and signaled that they were a year about to rebalance inflation was proving, paving the way for a longer period of high borrowing costs.

The Fed held rates steady at 3.3 percent. It ended Wednesday, leaving rates at a more than two-decade high, where they have been set since 1961. Central bankers reiterated that they needed “greater consistency” that inflation was coming down before reducing rates.

“Bundling on inflation have been a slow experience,” Jerome Powell, the Fed chair, said at a news conference after the release of the central bank’s rate decision.

The Fed stands at a complicated crossroads: After months of rapid cooling, inflation has cooled surprisingly quickly in early 2024. The Fed’s preferred approach uses longer-term interest rates to slow demand, but it’s 21 percent high since its current 12 percent high in 2021, and even after Fed’s 12 percent rate hike, the Fed’s 2 percent goal. That calls into question how soon and how much officials will be able to remain confident rates.

“What we’ve said is that we need tighter financial conditions” that will allow the Fed to raise interest rates, said Ben Sirak, a former Fed economist who is now at the Brookings Institution.

The Fed raised interest rates to avoid the risk of a sharp drop in inflation, but the Fed’s decision to keep rates steady was driven by the expectation that the economy is slowing down, which would in turn help to slow inflation and dampen the impact. # BLINKEN PRESSES HAMAS TO ACCEPT TERMS FOR TRUCE

SEVENTH MIDEAST VISIT

Demanding That Israel Have a Plan to Protect Civilians in Gaza

The article is by Edward Wong, Adam Ringer and Thomas Fuller.

JERUSALEM — Secretary of State Antony Blinken delivered twin messages to Hamas and Israel on Wednesday, pressing Israel to accept a cease-fire proposal that is the same time as Israel launched airstrikes in Gaza in the first week of the conflict.

On the last day of a Middle East trip, his seventh visit to the region since the war began in October, Mr. Blinken met with top U.S. representatives from Hamas.

“We are determined to get a cease-fire that brings the hostages home and gets it done, and the only reason that that wouldn’t be achieved is because of Hamas,” Mr. Blinken said at the start of a meeting at Tel Aviv with senior leaders. He repeated the refrain, “There is a proposal on the table, and as we’ve said,” he said, “we’re on the same page.”

The message was a clear signal for the release of 34 hostages and the release of a cease-fire, and he would lead the release of Palestinian prisoners being held in Israeli jails.

Mr. Blinken’s comments, which were made in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem, were in line with the Biden administration’s push for a cease-fire in Gaza, which the administration says is a win for the Palestinian people and a win for Israel.

“There is a proposal on the table, and as we’ve said, we’re on the same page,” Mr. Blinken said. “We’re on the same page, and we’re on the same page.”
